I often think that Millennials might be the last generation capable of purely appreciating art and forming connections with artists. They don't have that pressure, nor do they need to scrutinize everything through a critical, colored lens.
We grew up during the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, something that has since disappeared from collective consciousness.
Back then, we could immerse ourselves directly in the content without considering its origins, because tracing back its sources was not easy in those days.
We revered these artists as if they were deities, and there was no reason to question this adoration. Thus, we established a "pseudosocial relationship" with them, regarding it as an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
When the TV show "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would gather together every Thursday to watch it while eating pizza.
This is vastly different from our current experience of watching shows on streaming platforms. Streaming services usually release 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches at their own pace. When discussing plot points on social media, people often add a "spoiler warning" or simply communicate within specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all long to relive that sense of collective belonging that connected everyone.
It is precisely this nostalgia that drives us to rewatch shows like "The Office" or movies like "The Anchorman," whose unforgettable lines spread online like memes.
We quote these classic lines from the works and assume most people will understand them.
Nowadays, even if something goes viral online, we can no longer assume that everyone has seen it.
With the explosion of information, there are simply too many things for us to pay attention to, making it impossible to simplify... Do we still have a chance to escape from this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find that they are either notorious sexual predators or stubborn individuals full of prejudice, and this cycle is tiring.
On one hand, we are immersed in nostalgia, but on the other hand, we have to admit that the people who created the artworks we love may have serious moral flaws, and this conflicting mindset leaves us feeling helpless.
We will be even more careful in forming "pseudosocial relationships" with artists.
We are gradually realizing that if a person wants to gain wealth and power, it is difficult to ensure that they will not hurt or exploit others.
Since the collective consciousness of media no longer exists, we have developed a class consciousness, which helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are still some people who stubbornly insist on elevating others to a god-like status, and when the idol falls, they pretend to be shocked.
We are in an era of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
